## The action grid your stores price on — this is critical

Your store managers do **not** price continuously. Each store picks a price from a **discrete grid of {{ grid.m }} levels**, from **{{ grid.lo }} €** to **{{ grid.hi }} €**, evenly spaced **{{ grid.step }} € apart**. Consequences you MUST respect:

- A change to `p_bar` **smaller than {{ grid.step }} €** snaps back to the same grid point and **moves no store** — it is wasted. To shift your stores up by one notch, raise `p_bar` by **at least {{ grid.step }} €**.
- Your price band must contain **at least 2 grid points** so your stores have room to react to local competition. A band narrower than {{ grid.step }} € on both sides collapses to a single forced price.
{% if grid.regime == 'CS' %}
- **Each chain type prices on its OWN grid.** Your grid runs {{ grid.lo }}–{{ grid.hi }} € (step {{ grid.step }} €). Rivals of other types sit on **shifted** grids: {% for ct, g in grid.other_chain_grids.items() %}{{ ct }} {{ g.lo }}–{{ g.hi }} € (step {{ g.step }} €){{ "; " if not loop.last }}{% endfor %}. When you compare your price to a cross-type rival's, remember you are not on the same lattice.
{% else %}
