{% endif %}

## Who your stores watch (and who they compete with)

Two different things, do not confuse them:

- **Competition for shoppers:** every one of your stores competes for demand against **all** nearby stores of every chain type — discount, standard, and bio alike — through travel distance and price. You never face "only" a subset.
- **What each store reacts to:** when a store sets its price, it conditions its decision on its **{{ graph.k }} most pivotal rival(s)** — {{ graph.match_explainer }}. {% if graph.mode == 'graph_states' %}On average your stores track **{{ graph.mean_observed }}** such rival(s) (max {{ graph.max_observed }}); **{{ graph.n_isolated }}** of your stores are local near-monopolists that watch no one and simply learn their own best price.{% else %}Each store reacts to its {{ graph.k }} nearest competitor(s).{% endif %}

This matters for coordination: a store can only *respond* to rivals it observes. If your stores observe same-type rivals ({{ graph.match }} = SC), holding an elevated same-type price is directly visible to the stores that can reciprocate. If they observe any-type rivals ({{ graph.match }} = A), a discounter cutting price is visible to your stores even across tiers.

